New issue

Artifact deploy failing with message: fatal: pathspec '.' did not match any files #3529

Closed
jose-oliveira opened this issue on Apr 8, 2019 8 comments Fixed by #3530

Comments

Copy link
Contributor

jose-oliveira commented on Apr 8, 2019

  • [ X ] I have read and understand the contribution guidelines for new issues.

Describe the bug
Running:
vendor/bin/blt artifact:deploy --commit-msg "Test commit" --ignore-dirty --no-interaction --verbose -Dgit.remotes.1='REMOTE' --branch=BRANCH

Throws:

fatal: pathspec '.' did not match any files [ExecStack] Exit code 128 Time 0.014s [error] Failed to commit deployment artifact!

Expected behavior
Artifact to be deployed.

Additional context
This seems to happen because the repo doesn't have any files yet, so the command fails to remove all files as none exists. Adding --ignore-unmatch fixes it.

System information

  • Operating system type: MacOS
  • Operating system version: Mojave
  • BLT version: 10.0.0-rc-2

Contributor

timcosgrove commented on Apr 8, 2019
edited

Just confirming we are seeing this in BLT 9.2.6 also, presumably due to 43a5965

It makes sense that this would fail if the repo is created fresh (which is largely what would happen in CI scenarios). The order of operations is:

  1. create new directory if it does not exist (this is the usual case on CI unless there is file caching happening)
  2. cd into this empty directory.
  3. git init
  4. (config setting)
  5. git rm -r --cached .

Which indeed fails if you have a fresh git repo with no files in it.

christopher-hopper commented on Apr 15, 2019
edited

We're seeing this problem when running blt deploy --tag on an existing repository with heaps of stuff in it. I guess it is because a tag is unique and will never have anything in it to remove?

Here's the command.

deploy --commit-msg="Automated build by $(git config user.name) of $(git describe --tags --abbrev=0)" --tag="$(git describe --tags --abbrev=0)-build" --no-interaction --ansi --verbose

So the solution, I'm guessing by reading above, would be for me to add this additional argument/parameter --ignore-unmatch

EDIT:
Okay, just went through the commit logs and pull-request merges. Seems this --ignore-unmatch was added to the 10.x branch, but not yet in my BLT 9.2.6 so I can take it as a patch until 9.2.x is updated I guess.
